quat_to_euler <- function(qx, qy, qz, qw) {

  # roll (x)
  sinr_cosp <- 2 * (qw * qx + qy * qz)
  cosr_cosp <- 1 - 2 * (qx^2 + qy^2)
  roll <- atan2(sinr_cosp, cosr_cosp)

  # pitch (y)
  sinp <- 2 * (qw * qy - qz * qx)
  pitch <- ifelse(abs(sinp) >= 1, sign(sinp) * pi/2, asin(sinp))

  # yaw (z)
  siny_cosp <- 2 * (qw * qz + qx * qy)
  cosy_cosp <- 1 - 2 * (qy^2 + qz^2)
  yaw <- atan2(siny_cosp, cosy_cosp)

  return(c(roll, pitch, yaw))
}

Knees

For knees, we only keep 1 angle (roll - X) because the main rotation happens around the X axis. “No, you don’t need to control all three angles (flexion, extension, and rotation) in the knee joint for typical daily activities. The knee primarily functions with flexion and extension (bending and straightening). While there’s some degree of rotational movement, it’s minimal and primarily occurs with the ankle and hip joints.”

Knee Left
